@startuml 30_rag_validation_pipeline
!theme plain
title DRE 3D Framework -- RAG + Multi-Layer Validation Pipeline\nCAG + CRAG + Security + Governance + Validation + SQL Optimization

skinparam sequence {
  ArrowColor #546E7A
  LifeLineBorderColor #B0BEC5
  ParticipantBorderColor #90A4AE
  ParticipantBackgroundColor #ECEFF1
}
skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #FFFDE7
  BorderColor #F9A825
}

participant "User" as User
participant "Query\nOptimizer\n(LLM)" as QueryOpt
participant "CAG\nPre-Loader\n(Static)" as CAG
participant "CRAG\nRetrieval\nEvaluator" as CRAG
participant "Vector Search" as VS
participant "SQL Generator\n(LLM)" as SQLGen
participant "Security\nGuard\n(Rule-based)" as SecGuard
participant "Governance\nLayer\n(PII Check)" as GovLayer
participant "SQL Optimizer\n(LLM)" as SQLOpt
participant "Duplicate\nDetector\n(RAG + LLM)" as DupDetect
participant "SQL Validator\n(Rule + LLM)" as SQLVal
participant "Approval\nGateway" as Approval
database "Delta Tables" as Delta

== Stage 1: Query Understanding & Optimization ==

User -> QueryOpt : Raw NL query\n"Check nulls in customer emails"

note over QueryOpt
  <b>LLM-based query optimizer</b>
  - Extract entities (table, column, check type)
  - Expand abbreviations
  - Add domain context
  - Detect ambiguity
  - Rewrite for clarity
end note

QueryOpt -> QueryOpt : Extract:\ntable = "customer"\ncolumn = "email"\ncheck_type = "null_rate"

QueryOpt -> User : Clarification needed?
User -> QueryOpt : Confirm

== Stage 2: CAG -- Static Context Pre-Load ==

QueryOpt -> CAG : get_static_context()

note over CAG
  <b>Context-Augmented Generation</b>
  Pre-loaded static docs (once per session):
  - supported_checks.md (all valid check types)
  - security_patterns.json (forbidden patterns)
  - governance_rules.json (PII tables/columns)
  ~3,200 tokens -- always in system prompt
end note

CAG --> QueryOpt : {supported_checks, security_rules, pii_catalog}

== Stage 3: CRAG -- Dynamic Context Retrieval with Confidence Gate ==

QueryOpt -> CRAG : retrieve_context(\nquery, table, check_type)

CRAG -> VS : embed_and_search(\nquery="null_rate customer email",\ntop_k=8,\nfilter={table="customer", doc_type="sql_pattern"})

VS --> CRAG : top_k chunks + similarity_scores

note over CRAG
  <b>Corrective RAG with confidence gating:</b>
  1. Evaluate retrieval quality
  2. Coverage score (entities present?)
  3. Confidence = weighted avg of top-3 scores
  
  Thresholds:
  - HIGH (>=0.72): use as-is
  - MEDIUM (0.50-0.72): rewrite query + retry
  - LOW (<0.50): keyword fallback
end note

CRAG -> CRAG : confidence = 0.85 (HIGH)

CRAG --> QueryOpt : {context_chunks, confidence: HIGH}

== Stage 4: SQL Generation ==

QueryOpt -> SQLGen : generate_sql(\ncag_context + crag_context +\nentities + check_type)

note over SQLGen
  <b>LLM generates SQL grounded by:</b>
  - CAG: supported check types
  - CRAG: similar SQL patterns
  - Entities: table_fqn, column_name
  
  Output: SQL + explanation
end note

SQLGen --> QueryOpt : {sql: "SELECT...", explanation: "..."}

== Stage 5: Security Guard (Rule-Based) ==

QueryOpt -> SecGuard : validate_security(sql)

note over SecGuard
  <b>Rule-based security checks:</b>
  1. SELECT-only enforcement
  2. Block forbidden keywords:
     DROP, CREATE, ALTER, INSERT,
     UPDATE, DELETE, TRUNCATE, EXEC
  3. Block injection patterns:
     xp_cmdshell, OPENROWSET, BULK
  4. No dynamic SQL / EXEC()
  5. No multi-statement (semicolon check)
end note

alt SQL contains forbidden pattern
  SecGuard --> QueryOpt : REJECTED: "DROP keyword detected"
  QueryOpt -> User : Security violation
else Security passed
  SecGuard --> QueryOpt : PASSED
end

== Stage 6: Governance Layer (PII & Policy Check) ==

QueryOpt -> GovLayer : check_governance(sql, table, column)

note over GovLayer
  <b>Governance checks using CAG catalog:</b>
  1. Is table PII-sensitive? (from pii_catalog)
  2. Is column PII? (email, SSN, credit card)
  3. Does user have data access rights?
  4. Compliance requirements (GDPR, SOX)
  5. Anonymization required?
  6. Requires additional approval?
end note

GovLayer -> Delta : query: data_catalog_pii_metadata

alt Table/column is PII
  GovLayer --> QueryOpt : WARNING: PII detected\nRequires DataGovernance approval
  QueryOpt -> QueryOpt : Set approval_level = DataGovernance
else Not PII
  GovLayer --> QueryOpt : PASSED
end

== Stage 7: SQL Optimization (LLM) ==

QueryOpt -> SQLOpt : optimize_sql(sql)

note over SQLOpt
  <b>LLM-based SQL optimizer:</b>
  1. Add partition filters if available
  2. Push down predicates
  3. Use indexed columns where possible
  4. Estimate query cost (DBU)
  5. Suggest LIMIT for exploratory queries
  6. Check for Cartesian products
  7. Validate column exists in schema
  
  <b>Uses Unity Catalog metadata:</b>
  - INFORMATION_SCHEMA.COLUMNS
  - Table statistics
  - Partition keys
end note

SQLOpt -> Delta : query: UC metadata for table
Delta --> SQLOpt : schema + stats

SQLOpt -> SQLOpt : Add partition filter:\nWHERE event_date >= current_date - 30

SQLOpt --> QueryOpt : {optimized_sql, improvements, cost_estimate}

== Stage 8: Duplicate Detection (RAG + LLM Semantic Check) ==

QueryOpt -> DupDetect : check_duplicate(\noptimized_sql, table, column, check_type)

note over DupDetect
  <b>Semantic + Structural duplicate check:</b>
  1. RAG: retrieve similar active rules
  2. LLM: compare semantic intent
  3. Structural: same table + column + check_type?
  4. Functional: logically equivalent SQL?
  
  Uses:
  - Vector search on existing rule SQL
  - LLM judges similarity
end note

DupDetect -> VS : embed_and_search(\nsql_embedding, top_k=5,\nfilter={table, is_active=true})

VS --> DupDetect : similar_rules[]

DupDetect -> DupDetect : LLM: compare intent

alt Similar rule exists (>85% match)
  DupDetect --> QueryOpt : DUPLICATE FOUND\nExisting rule: DQ_20260501_003\nSimilarity: 92%
  QueryOpt -> User : Rule already exists.\nView existing rule?
else No duplicate
  DupDetect --> QueryOpt : NO_DUPLICATE
end

== Stage 9: SQL Validation (Rule-Based + LLM) ==

QueryOpt -> SQLVal : validate_sql(optimized_sql)

note over SQLVal
  <b>Hybrid validation (Rule + LLM):</b>
  
  <b>Rule-based:</b>
  - Syntax check (SQL parser)
  - Table exists in UC?
  - Column exists in table?
  - Data type compatibility
  - Aggregation logic valid?
  
  <b>LLM-based:</b>
  - Logical correctness
  - Does SQL match user intent?
  - Edge case handling
  - NULL handling correct?
  - Threshold makes sense?
end note

SQLVal -> Delta : query: DESCRIBE table_fqn
Delta --> SQLVal : schema

alt Validation fails
  SQLVal --> QueryOpt : INVALID: Column 'email' not found
  QueryOpt -> User : Validation error
else Validation passed
  SQLVal --> QueryOpt : VALID\nQuality score: 9.2/10
end

== Stage 10: Approval Routing ==

QueryOpt -> Approval : route_approval(\nrule, approval_level, pii_flag)

note over Approval
  <b>Approval routing logic:</b>
  - Owner: auto-approve
  - Non-owner: PO/TL approval
  - PII table: DataGovernance approval
  - High cost (>100 DBU): TL approval
  - Timeout: 72h -> escalate
end note

alt PII or non-owner
  Approval -> User : Approval request sent\nSLA: 48 hours
else Owner + non-PII
  Approval -> Delta : INSERT rule (is_active=true)
  Approval -> User : Rule created successfully
end

legend right
  <b>Summary: Multi-Layer Validation Pipeline</b>
  
  <b>Stage 1: Query Optimization (LLM)</b>
    - Extracts entities, expands abbreviations
    - Detects ambiguity, clarifies intent
  
  <b>Stage 2: CAG (Static Context)</b>
    - Pre-loaded: supported checks, security rules, PII catalog
    - Always available, no retrieval cost
  
  <b>Stage 3: CRAG (Dynamic Retrieval + Confidence Gate)</b>
    - Retrieves SQL patterns, examples, contracts
    - Confidence gating: HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW
    - Query rewrite on MEDIUM, fallback on LOW
  
  <b>Stage 4: SQL Generation (LLM + CAG + CRAG)</b>
    - LLM generates SQL grounded by context
  
  <b>Stage 5: Security Guard (Rule-Based)</b>
    - SELECT-only, block DROP/INSERT/DELETE
    - Injection pattern detection
  
  <b>Stage 6: Governance Layer (CAG Catalog)</b>
    - PII detection, compliance checks
    - Approval level routing
  
  <b>Stage 7: SQL Optimization (LLM + UC Metadata)</b>
    - Add partitions, push predicates, cost estimate
  
  <b>Stage 8: Duplicate Detection (RAG + LLM)</b>
    - Semantic + structural similarity
    - Prevent redundant rules
  
  <b>Stage 9: SQL Validation (Rule + LLM)</b>
    - Syntax, schema, logical correctness
  
  <b>Stage 10: Approval Gateway</b>
    - Route based on owner, PII, cost
  
  <b>Answer: LLM or RAG for SQL validation?</b>
  <b>BOTH:</b>
  - <b>LLM</b> for generation, optimization, logical validation
  - <b>RAG</b> for grounding, duplicate detection, pattern retrieval
  - <b>Rule-based</b> for security, syntax, schema checks
  
  <b>CAG vs CRAG:</b>
  - <b>CAG</b>: small static docs, always loaded
  - <b>CRAG</b>: large dynamic corpus, confidence-gated retrieval
endlegend

@enduml
